A Doubleton Class is a design pattern where only two objects of a class can be created in the entire application.

It is similar to the Singleton pattern:
Singleton → only 1 object
Doubleton → only 2 objects

Real-Time Example
Imagine a system where only two database connections are allowed.

Example:
Connection-1
Connection-2

If a third request comes, the class should return one of the existing two objects instead of creating a new one.

==>How Doubleton Works
Constructor is made private
Create two static objects inside the class
Provide a static method to return one of the two objects
Prevent new object creation using new

Interview Answer
In a banking application, Doubleton pattern can be used to manage only two server connections: one Primary Server and one Backup Server.
Customer requests are routed between these two servers for load balancing and failover handling.
The application reuses the same two server objects instead of creating new connections every time.
This improves performance, controls resource usage, and provides high availability in banking transactions.